HUEGO – Project Architecture
1. High-Level Overview

Huego is a full-stack web application for discovering, liking, and organizing color palettes.

The project is divided into two independent layers:

Frontend → React + TypeScript (UI & user interaction)

Backend → Node.js + TypeScript (API & data handling)

Both layers live in a single monorepo for easier development and deployment.

HUEGO/
├── backend/     → API, business logic, database
└── frontend/    → UI, components, user experience

2. Backend Architecture (/backend)

The backend is responsible for:

Serving palette data

Handling likes / favorites

Managing API endpoints

Interacting with the database

backend/
├── src/                 → Source code
│   ├── routes/          → API route definitions
│   ├── controllers/     → Request → Response logic
│   ├── services/        → Business logic
│   ├── models/          → Database schemas / types
│   └── index.ts         → App entry point
│
├── dist/                → Compiled JS output (build)
├── node_modules/
├── .env                 → Environment variables
├── package.json
├── tsconfig.json

Backend Flow
Client Request
   ↓
Route
   ↓
Controller
   ↓
Service
   ↓
Database
   ↓
Response


The backend is stateless and exposes a REST API consumed by the frontend.

3. Frontend Architecture (/frontend)

The frontend is a component-driven React application written in TypeScript.

Its responsibilities:

Rendering palettes

Handling user interactions (like, favorite)

Fetching data from backend APIs

Managing UI state

frontend/
├── public/              → Static assets
├── src/
│   ├── assets/          → Images, icons
│   ├── components/      → Reusable UI components
│   │
│   ├── CollectionSection/
│   │   ├── CollectionSection.tsx
│   │   └── CollectionSection.css
│   │
│   ├── FavouriteSection/
│   │   ├── FavouriteSection.tsx
│   │   └── FavouriteSection.css
│   │
│   ├── PaletteGrid/
│   │   ├── PaletteGrid.tsx
│   │   └── PaletteGrid.css
│   │
│   ├── PaletteCard/
│   │   ├── PaletteCard.tsx
│   │   └── PaletteCard.css
│   │
│   ├── LikeButton/
│   │   ├── LikeButton.tsx
│   │   └── LikeButton.css
│   │
│   ├── Header/
│   ├── LeftSideBar/
│   ├── PaletteDetails/
│   │
│   ├── App.tsx          → App root
│   └── main.tsx         → Entry point
│
├── package.json

4. Component Philosophy

Huego follows a UI-first, composable architecture.

Small components do one thing well

Sections compose multiple components

Pages compose sections

Example:

PaletteGrid
 ├── PaletteCard
 │    ├── LikeButton
 │    └── ColorPreview
 └── Pagination / Filters


This keeps the UI:

Reusable

Testable

Easy to extend

5. Data Flow (Frontend ↔ Backend)
User Action (Like Palette)
        ↓
React Component
        ↓
API Call (fetch / axios)
        ↓
Backend Route
        ↓
Database Update
        ↓
Updated Response
        ↓
UI Re-render


The frontend never directly accesses the database — all communication goes through the backend API.

6. Styling Strategy

Each component has its own CSS file

Styles are scoped by convention

No global CSS pollution

Easy to refactor or migrate to CSS Modules / Tailwind later

7. Why This Architecture?

✔ Clear separation of concerns
✔ Scales well as features grow
✔ Easy for new contributors to understand
✔ Production-ready structure

This architecture intentionally avoids premature complexity while leaving room for:

Authentication

Caching

Server-side rendering

Mobile clients

AI-based palette generation

8. Future Improvements (Planned)

Centralized API service layer (frontend)

Global state management (Context / Zustand)

Authentication & user profiles

Rate limiting & caching

Testing (unit + integration)

9. Summary

Huego is built with:

Simple mental model

Modern best practices

Real-world scalability in mind

If you’re new to the project, start here:

frontend/src/components

backend/src/routes

Follow the data flow


